{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01K1N8w9BZr6SRCw2JjEhX8k","type":"tool_result","content":"1\timport { clickhouse } from \"@/lib/clickhouse\";\n2\timport type { EventRow } from \"@/lib/identity\";\n3\t\n4\t// ─── Type alias for the ClickHouse client ────────────────────────────────────\n5\t\n6\ttype ClickHouseClientLike = typeof clickhouse;\n7\t\n8\t// ─── queryNewEvents ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n9\t\n10\t/**\n11\t * Returns events ingested after sinceIngestedAt, joined with identity_mappings\n12\t * FINAL so that resolved_id is computed via coalesce(e.user_id, m.user_id,\n13\t * e.device_id). Events are ordered oldest-first (ingested_at ASC) and capped\n14\t * at 200 rows per call.\n15\t *\n16\t * sinceIngestedAt must be a ClickHouse-compatible datetime string\n17\t * (\"YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM:SS.mmm\").\n18\t */\n19\texport async function queryNewEvents(\n20\t  sinceIngestedAt: string,\n21\t  client: ClickHouseClientLike = clickhouse,\n22\t): Promise<EventRow[]> {\n23\t  const result = await client.query({\n24\t    query: `\n25\t      SELECT\n26\t        e.event_id,\n27\t        e.event_name,\n28\t        e.timestamp,\n29\t        e.device_id,\n30\t        e.user_id,\n31\t        e.properties,\n32\t        e.ingested_at,\n33\t        coalesce(e.user_id, m.user_id, e.device_id) AS resolved_id\n34\t      FROM events e\n35\t      LEFT JOIN (SELECT device_id, user_id FROM identity_mappings FINAL) m\n36\t        ON e.device_id = m.device_id\n37\t      WHERE e.ingested_at > {since:String}\n38\t      ORDER BY e.ingested_at ASC, e.event_id ASC\n39\t      LIMIT 200\n40\t    `,\n41\t    query_params: { since: sinceIngestedAt },\n42\t    format: \"JSONEachRow\",\n43\t  });\n44\t\n45\t  return result.json<EventRow>();\n46\t}\n47\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"496fb2ae-93e4-48b2-b968-7ed4da55eb0e","uuid":"a2c517d0-3a6e-4967-8133-22a1584c71d3","timestamp":"2026-04-15T18:03:33.154Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/riccardocaranfil/bitrefill/minipanel-blank-night-2/src/lib/live.ts","content":"import { clickhouse } from \"@/lib/clickhouse\";\nimport type { EventRow } from \"@/lib/identity\";\n\n// ─── Type alias for the ClickHouse client ────────────────────────────────────\n\ntype ClickHouseClientLike = typeof clickhouse;\n\n// ─── queryNewEvents ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n\n/**\n * Returns events ingested after sinceIngestedAt, joined with identity_mappings\n * FINAL so that resolved_id is computed via coalesce(e.user_id, m.user_id,\n * e.device_id). Events are ordered oldest-first (ingested_at ASC) and capped\n * at 200 rows per call.\n *\n * sinceIngestedAt must be a ClickHouse-compatible datetime string\n * (\"YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM:SS.mmm\").\n */\nexport async function queryNewEvents(\n  sinceIngestedAt: string,\n  client: ClickHouseClientLike = clickhouse,\n): Promise<EventRow[]> {\n  const result = await client.query({\n    query: `\n      SELECT\n        e.event_id,\n        e.event_name,\n        e.timestamp,\n        e.device_id,\n        e.user_id,\n        e.properties,\n        e.ingested_at,\n        coalesce(e.user_id, m.user_id, e.device_id) AS resolved_id\n      FROM events e\n      LEFT JOIN (SELECT device_id, user_id FROM identity_mappings FINAL) m\n        ON e.device_id = m.device_id\n      WHERE e.ingested_at > {since:String}\n      ORDER BY e.ingested_at ASC, e.event_id ASC\n      LIMIT 200\n    `,\n    query_params: { since: sinceIngestedAt },\n    format: \"JSONEachRow\",\n  });\n\n  return result.json<EventRow>();\n}\n","numLines":47,"startLine":1,"totalLines":47}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01HW5qS2gSDvt3RND873TXH5","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a complete picture. Let me look at the existing test file for QuickFireButtons to understand the component testing approach, then look at any component test files that use jsdom and React Testing Library.\n\nKey observations from existing tests:\n1. They use `// @vitest-environment jsdom` at the top of test files that render React components\n2. They use `@testing-library/react` for rendering and interaction\n3. For hook tests, they use `renderHook` from `@testing-library/react`\n4. They mock `fetch` using `vi.stubGlobal`\n\nFor the `useLiveFeed` hook, I need to mock `EventSource` (the browser's SSE API).\n\n\nNow I'm planning the test structure for `useLiveFeed`. I'll need to mock the `EventSource` API since the hook establishes an SSE connection to `/api/live` on mount, parses incoming messages as `EventRow` objects, maintains a capped list of 200 events in newest-first order, handles pause/resume with buffering, and tracks connection status.\n\nFor the hook tests, I'm covering the initial disconnected state, how SSE messages get prepended to the list, the 200-event cap that drops oldest entries, pause behavior with buffering, resume flushing, clearing events, connection status transitions, and cleanup on unmount. Then for the component tests, I'll verify the connection status indicator renders correctly.\n\nNow I need to mock EventSource for the hook tests and implement both test suites. For the hook itself, I'll manage events in newest-first order, track pause state and connection status, and use a ref to hold the EventSource instance.\n\nImplementing the hook... Setting up the event stream connection and handling incoming messages...\n\nWhen pausing, I buffer incoming events, and when resuming I flush that buffer back into the main events list while respecting the max event limit. I also have a clear function to reset both the events and buffer. Now I'm noticing a potential issue with how the pause toggle handles the state update — when resuming and flushing the buffer, I need to make sure the ordering and limits are applied correctly. Now I'm verifying the buffer order - when events arrive as A, B, C (oldest to newest), they get prepended so the buffer is [C, B, A], and when flushing with `[...buffered, ...events]`, that gives the correct newest-first ordering. For the EventSource mock, I need a class that can be instantiated with a URL, supports `onopen`, `onmessage`, and `onerror` handlers, has a `close()` method, and lets tests simulate the event lifecycle. Now I'm structuring the LiveFeed component...\n\nBuilding the component... Writing the LiveFeed component... Writing the mock EventSource...\n\nI need to set the vitest environment to jsdom for this test file since the hook is a client component that relies on browser APIs like EventSource and useState. I need to set up the EventSource mock globally in the test environment, and I'll mock the `useLiveFeed` hook in the LiveFeed component tests so I can control what it returns. Let me verify the testing libraries available—`@testing-library/react` version 16 has `renderHook`, and I'll use `fireEvent` since `user-event` isn't in the dependencies. Now I'm ready to write out the test and implementation files in order.\n\nLet me check the tsconfig path mapping...","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4880,"cache_read_input_tokens":44800,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4880},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"496fb2ae-93e4-48b2-b968-7ed4da55eb0e","uuid":"c31c3802-9fb1-45fe-9960-dc43055d10fa"}
